full_text: This is really important. People sometimes point to U6 as the “real unemployment rate”. And perhaps it is, in some sense, a better measure of labor market health than U3. But by definition it’s always the higher of the two numbers.
name: Joe Weisenthal

full_text: So at any given time, what matters is comparing U6 to other times. Or comparing the evolution of the U3-U6 spread. But either way, simply asserting that U6 (or other derivatives) is “the real story” is the domain of charlatans and knaves.
name: Joe Weisenthal

full_text:
Conceptually, it makes sense for the government to hold "strategic" stockpiles of any asset that:

A) It could presumably have a liability in, at some point
B) It can't instantly acquire with money

So for example, oil (especially when we didn't produce much here) made sense.
name: Joe Weisenthal

full_text: Military equipment is like this as well. One could argue that in a war, we have bullet-denominated liabilities. Or tank-denominated liabilities. \n\nAnd you can't acquire bullets or tanks out of thin air with money, due to the time to ramp up production.
name: Joe Weisenthal

full_text: In all seriousness, my view on Efficient Markets is basically this.\n\nIf you look at a line and think it's mis-priced, you should start by assuming you're wrong. Then dive in further and see if you missed something, and then still assume that you're wrong. 1/2

full_text: And then after repeating that process a number of times, and you come to the conclusion that some security is mis-priced. Then you should assume you, personally, won't be able to profit from the mis-pricing.

full_text:
Where did the meme come from that the stock market is not the economy?

A lot of people have exposure to stocks so it has (at least some) bearing on spending decisions.

And (real) investment decisions are (often) predicated on being able to sell assets to outside investors?
name: Joe Weisenthal

full_text: OF COURSE there are people who are struggling, even amidst a bull market. OF COURSE for most households, their wage and employment status is of more importance than their stock portfolio, day to day. But I think generally people are too dismissive of its significance.

full_text:
CREATIVE DESTRUCTION WITHOUT THE CREATION

In the Odd Lots newsletter, I wrote about what I see as the problem with the "no pain no gain" characterization of recent volatility. The premise is fine. There's just something missing.

Get the newsletter here: https://t.co/25c7dc8ulW https://t.co/I3hLt3FaZv
name: Joe Weisenthal

full_text: RT @MattZeitlin: https://t.co/0Cq4tA14Yk
name: Joe Weisenthal

full_text: This a key thing here. Lower inflation allows the Fed to lower rates. And lower rates drives more economic activity.\n\nBut if you're not expanding economic capacity, then lowering activity to get lower rates to drive more activity is just like gaining weight in order to lose it.
name: Joe Weisenthal

full_text: To be fair, the admin does want more productive manufacturing capacity in the US. But ideally that expanded capacity comes from technological advance/automation. As it stands, we're looking at protecting existing processes while diminishing investment due to lower profits.
name: Joe Weisenthal

full_text: There's debate about whether "running the economy hot" leads to more productivity, as firms are forced to make technological investment. People hated the high inflation of the last few years, but at least in certain areas of tech, it was a period of high investment intensity.
name: Joe Weisenthal

full_text: I don't think you can draw an easy line (unfortunately) between the economic heat of the last few years, and all the investment in AI, chips, datacenters etc.  But I think the alternative is plausible. That we'd have seen a lower willingness to invest in a down economy.
name: Joe Weisenthal
